01:20:23.035 --> 01:20:24.515
about your dad...

01:20:24.602 --> 01:20:25.995
fucking everything in L.A.
but his wife,

01:20:26.082 --> 01:20:27.692
it doesn't
hurt as bad,

01:20:27.779 --> 01:20:30.782
because you've kind of gone
through way worse.

01:20:30.869 --> 01:20:32.784
So you know,
as far as...

01:20:32.871 --> 01:20:34.786
My mom's relationship
with it,

01:20:34.873 --> 01:20:37.223
she has to believe
what she has to believe in,

01:20:37.310 --> 01:20:38.746
and I respect that,

01:20:38.834 --> 01:20:40.661
and she very well could be
right, you know,

01:20:40.748 --> 01:20:42.620
but for me
to get by,

01:20:42.707 --> 01:20:44.013
and for me to accept

01:20:44.100 --> 01:20:45.275
in any way,
shape, or form

01:20:45.362 --> 01:20:46.711
what kind of a man
he was,

01:20:46.798 --> 01:20:48.234
then I had
to be okay with...

01:20:48.321 --> 01:20:51.063
with how I perceived it
and how I saw it.

01:20:51.150 --> 01:20:52.978
When someone dies,
the last thing

01:20:53.065 --> 01:20:55.938
you think of is,
"Did they do the dishes?"

01:20:56.025 --> 01:20:57.765
You're like,
"Oh, my God, I hope...

01:20:57.853 --> 01:20:59.811
he had enough sex, I hope
he was happy--" you know?

01:20:59.898 --> 01:21:01.160
It's awful.

01:21:01.247 --> 01:21:02.379
You know,
once we started speaking

01:21:02.466 --> 01:21:03.902
honestly about
ourselves,

01:21:03.989 --> 01:21:05.599
and having
a point of view

01:21:05.686 --> 01:21:09.299
and not just being,
you know, a type of clown.

01:21:09.386 --> 01:21:11.083
Once comics started
to talk out loud

01:21:11.170 --> 01:21:13.607
about their life
and life around them,

01:21:13.694 --> 01:21:15.392
people made this assumption,
like, "Oh, they got--

01:21:15.479 --> 01:21:18.264
They're all
incredibly fucked up."

01:21:18.351 --> 01:21:20.658
But I don't-- I think
that's a mischaracterization.

01:21:20.745 --> 01:21:22.138
You know, I...

01:21:22.225 --> 01:21:24.096
I think that struggle
is necessary,

01:21:24.183 --> 01:21:27.273
but I don't think
misery is necessary.

01:21:27.360 --> 01:21:29.319
You know
what's an interesting thing?

01:21:29.406 --> 01:21:31.147
Maybe you have to be insecure
to be funny.

01:21:31.234 --> 01:21:32.496
Maybe that's part of it.

01:21:32.583 --> 01:21:34.193
You don't have to be
miserable.

01:21:34.280 --> 01:21:35.978
But there has to be
something wrong with you.

01:21:36.065 --> 01:21:38.197
[laughing]

01:21:38.284 --> 01:21:39.982
I don't think in theory

01:21:40.069 --> 01:21:43.986
one needs to be miserable
to be funny.

01:21:44.073 --> 01:21:45.813
But I don't know
anyone close to me

01:21:45.901 --> 01:21:49.295
that's not miserable.

01:21:49.382 --> 01:21:50.906
The people
I know really well

01:21:50.993 --> 01:21:53.865
that are the funniest
are the most miserable.

01:21:53.952 --> 01:21:56.999
I'm not miserable.

01:21:57.086 --> 01:22:00.176
I think
I'm just indifferent.

01:22:00.263 --> 01:22:02.004
I'm miserable
right now

01:22:02.091 --> 01:22:04.528
because of what I'm going
through with my finances,

01:22:04.615 --> 01:22:07.835
and, at 58, I didn't want
to be in this position,

01:22:07.923 --> 01:22:10.186
and whoever said
"money doesn't buy happiness,"

01:22:10.273 --> 01:22:12.884
I hope you're fucking dead,
'cause you're an idiot.

01:22:12.971 --> 01:22:14.277
'Cause
you know what?

01:22:14.364 --> 01:22:15.887
I'm only miserable

01:22:15.974 --> 01:22:17.497
because
I'm so depressed

01:22:17.584 --> 01:22:19.021
because I'm working
so hard for so little,

01:22:19.108 --> 01:22:20.631
but there's a lot of people

01:22:20.718 --> 01:22:23.286
doing a lot worse
than I am, you know?

01:22:23.373 --> 01:22:24.896
"At least you got
your health."

01:22:24.983 --> 01:22:26.289
Whatever Jewish idiot
said that, you're wrong.

01:22:26.376 --> 01:22:27.943
Health is good,
money is good.

01:22:28.030 --> 01:22:30.032
The combination is
just great.

01:22:30.119 --> 01:22:34.123
And I've talked
about this on stage a lot.

01:22:34.210 --> 01:22:37.213
I've suffered
from depression.

01:22:37.300 --> 01:22:41.086
Been on and off antidepressants
for the last...

01:22:41.173 --> 01:22:43.393
Probably ten years or so,

01:22:43.480 --> 01:22:45.090
and at times
I've been suicidal

01:22:45.177 --> 01:22:47.049
and not because of comedy,
but just, you know,

01:22:47.136 --> 01:22:48.920
other pressures
from the world,

01:22:49.007 --> 01:22:51.009
and whatever,
and I realized

01:22:51.096 --> 01:22:55.057
that happiness isn't...

01:22:55.144 --> 01:22:56.754
isn't all about
stand-up comedy,

01:22:56.841 --> 01:22:58.495
and I've only realized that
just recently,

01:22:58.582 --> 01:23:00.062
and people ask you
in interviews, they go,

01:23:00.149 --> 01:23:02.020
"How would you like to be
remembered?"

01:23:02.107 --> 01:23:03.717
And I've got
to come to terms with--

01:23:03.804 --> 01:23:06.416
I might not be remembered,
and that doesn't matter.

01:23:06.503 --> 01:23:08.548
The only thing
I care about now

01:23:08.635 --> 01:23:11.595
is how my son
remembers me.

01:23:11.682 --> 01:23:13.945
And if everyone else sorta
liked me, that's all right,

01:23:14.032 --> 01:23:17.340
but as long as he thinks I was
a good guy, you know--

01:23:17.427 --> 01:23:18.863
When my dad dies,
I don't think

01:23:18.950 --> 01:23:20.299
he was just a carpenter,

01:23:20.386 --> 01:23:21.822
I don't think
he's gonna be remembered

01:23:21.909 --> 01:23:23.389
by the whole world,

01:23:23.476 --> 01:23:25.913
but he'll be
remembered by me.

01:23:26.001 --> 01:23:28.220
And that's--

01:23:28.307 --> 01:23:31.180
I'm working on
making that more important

01:23:31.267 --> 01:23:34.096
than being remembered as
a great comedian.

01:23:34.183 --> 01:23:37.795
[Hardwick]
Everyone's miserable, everyone
has misery in their lives,

01:23:37.882 --> 01:23:40.450
but really, you know,
misery is just a form

01:23:40.537 --> 01:23:43.627
of dissatisfaction,
and so maybe--

01:23:43.714 --> 01:23:45.498
You know,
maybe comedy is really

01:23:45.585 --> 01:23:48.849
just taking dissatisfaction
and discomfort

01:23:48.936 --> 01:23:51.243
and spinning it

01:23:51.330 --> 01:23:53.028
in a way that helps you
deal with it,

01:23:53.115 --> 01:23:55.291
and then
people relate to it.

01:23:55.378 --> 01:23:58.555
Um, I think you at least
have to know misery.

01:23:58.642 --> 01:24:00.383
I don't think
comedians corner the market

01:24:00.470 --> 01:24:02.515
on loneliness and need
for attention,

01:24:02.602 --> 01:24:05.736
but I think they have
to know it, certainly.

01:24:05.823 --> 01:24:07.172
[Pollak]
Yeah.

01:24:07.259 --> 01:24:09.348
I think that's
where it comes from.

01:24:09.435 --> 01:24:11.046
Sort of a fear

01:24:11.133 --> 01:24:13.570
and...

01:24:13.657 --> 01:24:15.311
a protection of
that fear.

01:24:15.398 --> 01:24:17.052
To this day, I'm...

01:24:17.139 --> 01:24:18.401
there's nowhere that
I'm funnier

01:24:18.488 --> 01:24:20.229
than in a doctor's office,

01:24:20.316 --> 01:24:22.535
'cause I'm a little scared
and a little--

01:24:22.622 --> 01:24:24.494
I'm hilarious
in a doctor's office.

01:24:24.581 --> 01:24:26.148
I bartended for
a long time.

01:24:26.235 --> 01:24:28.846
Let me just tell you,
the general public's

01:24:28.933 --> 01:24:30.456
kinda miserable.

01:24:30.543 --> 01:24:33.285
I don't think
it's because--

01:24:33.372 --> 01:24:36.462
I think we just have
a faster track to misery,

01:24:36.549 --> 01:24:38.029
and it's more
available.

01:24:38.116 --> 01:24:39.596
I mean,
we walk into work,

01:24:39.683 --> 01:24:41.076
our job,

01:24:41.163 --> 01:24:42.512
and somebody goes,
"You want a shot?"

01:24:42.599 --> 01:24:44.905
Well, that doesn't
happen at IBM.

01:24:44.992 --> 01:24:46.690
You don't show up
at 9:00 in the morning,

01:24:46.777 --> 01:24:49.171
there's a guy with a bottle
of Peach Schnapps.

01:24:49.258 --> 01:24:50.824
"Hey, you in?"

01:24:50.911 --> 01:24:53.653
So if you are leaning
toward any bad habits,

01:24:53.740 --> 01:24:56.395
this is the perfect lifestyle
to engage in,

01:24:56.482 --> 01:24:58.136
but again,
rule follower.

01:24:58.223 --> 01:24:59.398
Control, I'm never gonna--

01:24:59.485 --> 01:25:00.878
I'm not shooting
heroin with you

01:25:00.965 --> 01:25:02.358
by the trash can
at 9:00.

01:25:02.445 --> 01:25:04.186
What, are you crazy?

01:25:04.273 --> 01:25:05.839
I do try to,
on some level,

01:25:05.926 --> 01:25:09.408
even if I'm telling a joke
about a gaping butthole,

01:25:09.495 --> 01:25:12.063
I do try to have it
colored by the fact

01:25:12.150 --> 01:25:14.892
that I like people,

01:25:14.979 --> 01:25:16.763
I enjoy being alive,

01:25:16.850 --> 01:25:18.591
and, um...

01:25:18.678 --> 01:25:20.289
[Pollak]
Gratefully, you don't
have a gaping butthole.

01:25:20.376 --> 01:25:21.768
Yeah, not yet,
you know?

01:25:21.855 --> 01:25:23.596
You know,
the self-loathing darkness

01:25:23.683 --> 01:25:25.642
where you wake up 3:00
in the morning and kinda go--

01:25:25.729 --> 01:25:27.122
but this is
an old Steve Martin bit

01:25:27.209 --> 01:25:28.645
where you just kind of,
like, go in,

01:25:28.732 --> 01:25:30.516
you sprinkle
some water on your face,

01:25:30.603 --> 01:25:32.388
and you look at yourself in
the mirror, and you say...

01:25:33.693 --> 01:25:35.434
"What is
happening to me?!"

01:25:35.521 --> 01:25:38.220
You know?[Pollak laughing]

01:25:38.307 --> 01:25:40.135
"Why am I in this hotel?"

01:25:40.222 --> 01:25:42.702
By the way, I figured that out
two-and-a-half years ago.

01:25:42.789 --> 01:25:44.922
[Pollak]
That's right.
That would be...

01:25:45.009 --> 01:25:48.882
54-and-a-half years of living
in self-loathing darkness,

01:25:48.969 --> 01:25:50.667
so you get past that,

01:25:50.754 --> 01:25:53.757
and things seem to be a little
bit better, don't they?

01:25:53.844 --> 01:25:58.240
I had a panic attack on stage
once that was terrifying,

01:25:58.327 --> 01:25:59.806
because I did not know

01:25:59.893 --> 01:26:02.157
there was such a thing
as panic attacks.

01:26:02.244 --> 01:26:05.421
The thought of
having to be on stage

01:26:05.508 --> 01:26:08.250
for another 50 minutes

01:26:08.337 --> 01:26:10.426
and then two more hours
after that

01:26:10.513 --> 01:26:13.603
was unendurable,

01:26:13.690 --> 01:26:17.433
and I walked offstage,

01:26:17.520 --> 01:26:19.783
and I walked
out of the club,

01:26:19.870 --> 01:26:21.437
and the club owner was
in the lobby,

01:26:21.524 --> 01:26:23.265
and he looked
at me, and he went,

01:26:23.352 --> 01:26:24.396
"Who's on stage
right now?"

01:26:24.483 --> 01:26:26.268
I just went, "No one."

01:26:26.355 --> 01:26:28.705
And I walked into
the men's room,

01:26:28.792 --> 01:26:31.142
and I just stood
in the stall for a minute,

01:26:31.229 --> 01:26:34.450
and it kinda passed.

01:26:34.537 --> 01:26:37.279
Then I finally get
to the right doctor,

01:26:37.366 --> 01:26:38.976
who said,

01:26:39.063 --> 01:26:41.370
"I think you might want
to take a pill for this."

01:26:41.457 --> 01:26:43.937
And he just--

01:26:44.024 --> 01:26:46.375
"Yeah, panic disorder.

01:26:46.462 --> 01:26:47.985
People have it."

01:26:48.072 --> 01:26:50.335
My sort of hippy-dippy
friends would say, like,

01:26:50.422 --> 01:26:52.337
"You know, you're still
feeling the anxiety,

01:26:52.424 --> 01:26:55.297
you're just
masking it with medication."

01:26:55.384 --> 01:26:58.125
And I go, "Yes."

01:26:58.213 --> 01:27:02.956
That's what it says on the label
of the prescription, "masks."

01:27:03.043 --> 01:27:04.654
In the winter,
I still feel the cold.

01:27:04.741 --> 01:27:08.266
I mask it with
a coat.

01:27:08.353 --> 01:27:09.920
Because I'm a coward.

01:27:10.007 --> 01:27:13.184
I wrote "Swingers" after
suffering from a breakup.

01:27:13.271 --> 01:27:15.534
That aspect was
autobiographical,

01:27:15.621 --> 01:27:19.321
and through the experience
of writing that thing

01:27:19.408 --> 01:27:21.845
alone in my rented room,

01:27:21.932 --> 01:27:24.500
I was pouring my heart and soul
into this thing,

01:27:24.587 --> 01:27:26.850
and then...

01:27:26.937 --> 01:27:28.852
By the time
I had to perform it,

01:27:28.939 --> 01:27:32.247
I wasn't really connected
with that pain anymore,

01:27:32.334 --> 01:27:34.727
and then,
by the time I showed it,

01:27:34.814 --> 01:27:36.642
there was laughter
and the opposite

01:27:36.729 --> 01:27:39.254
of the feeling
I felt in the breakup,

01:27:39.341 --> 01:27:41.517
because I was now connected

01:27:41.604 --> 01:27:44.128
with these thousands
of people around the world,

01:27:44.215 --> 01:27:47.131
and everybody who saw it
or a screening I went to,

01:27:47.218 --> 01:27:50.352
now I felt like I was
part of a collective,

01:27:50.439 --> 01:27:51.875
I felt like I was-- people
understood me,

01:27:51.962 --> 01:27:54.356
I understood them,
and we shared a heart.

01:27:54.443 --> 01:27:56.575
I've done a lot of plays in
Midtown, Broadway and whatever,

01:27:56.662 --> 01:27:58.273
and, like,
I'll do the walk,

01:27:58.360 --> 01:28:01.493
I'll do the 40-block walk,
full talking to myself,

01:28:01.580 --> 01:28:03.278
full talking to myself,

01:28:03.365 --> 01:28:05.323
reliving shit that
just happened,

01:28:05.410 --> 01:28:08.370
having full conversations with
people that I wanted to have,

01:28:08.457 --> 01:28:10.459
"Fucker, why the fuck
do you keep doing this?"

01:28:10.546 --> 01:28:12.069
Something like that,
you know,

01:28:12.156 --> 01:28:13.636
you want to have that
conversation, you don't,

01:28:13.723 --> 01:28:15.333
you have it with the other guy,
and you're like,

01:28:15.420 --> 01:28:16.421
"I swear, tomorrow,
I'm gonna say something."

01:28:16.508 --> 01:28:17.944
It doesn't happen,
but I--

01:28:18.031 --> 01:28:19.555
I get it all out,
like, in 40 blocks,

01:28:19.642 --> 01:28:21.339
walking and talking.

01:28:21.426 --> 01:28:23.428
Nobody fucking
bothers me.

01:28:23.515 --> 01:28:25.474
I think artists are,
you know, brave people,

01:28:25.561 --> 01:28:26.649
but we're fucked up.

01:28:26.736 --> 01:28:29.129
Yes, there are...

01:28:29.216 --> 01:28:32.698
really fucked-up people
in show business.

01:28:32.785 --> 01:28:34.439
The people
that talk about

01:28:34.526 --> 01:28:36.572
how fucked-up people are
in show business,

01:28:36.659 --> 01:28:39.923
have they met anyone
that's not in show business?

01:28:40.010 --> 01:28:41.490
The same pain,

01:28:41.577 --> 01:28:44.101
the same suffering,
the same angst,

01:28:44.188 --> 01:28:45.320
the same
tortures,

01:28:45.407 --> 01:28:46.625
the same doubts,

01:28:46.712 --> 01:28:48.932
the same misery are
all there.

01:28:49.019 --> 01:28:51.543
In show business,

01:28:51.630 --> 01:28:55.286
you show what
you're feeling.

01:28:55.373 --> 01:28:58.115
So, yes, they show
the angst,

01:28:58.202 --> 01:29:00.857
but they're showing
the angst of humanity,

01:29:00.944 --> 01:29:02.989
the angst
that we all share.

01:29:03.076 --> 01:29:05.209
If you had a comic

01:29:05.296 --> 01:29:07.733
that truly had
experiences

01:29:07.820 --> 01:29:10.736
that were
outside of the realm

01:29:10.823 --> 01:29:13.304
of the general
humanity,

01:29:13.391 --> 01:29:15.045
no one would
go see them.

01:29:15.132 --> 01:29:19.354
Right now, I'm still
making the decision of,

01:29:19.441 --> 01:29:21.312
am I a comedian?

01:29:21.399 --> 01:29:23.836
I shuffle
the job title

01:29:23.923 --> 01:29:26.796
on the web with what
I do first,

01:29:26.883 --> 01:29:29.189
depending on
what I'm doing.

01:29:29.276 --> 01:29:31.235
And I'm a comedian,
and I'm proud to be a comedian.

01:29:31.322 --> 01:29:33.455
It took me
a really long time

01:29:33.542 --> 01:29:34.717
to take out the word
"American"

01:29:34.804 --> 01:29:36.762
and put "comedian."

01:29:36.849 --> 01:29:40.157
Don't you take my truck,
I'm a comedian.

01:29:40.244 --> 01:29:42.333
You know, we'll do
a montage at the end.

01:29:42.420 --> 01:29:44.030
[Pollak chuckling]

01:29:44.117 --> 01:29:47.730
It can be viewed as
questionable babysitting.

01:29:47.817 --> 01:29:49.775
I'm in charge of
these people,

01:29:49.862 --> 01:29:51.603
but I shouldn't be.

01:29:51.690 --> 01:29:54.171
But I am, and let's just hope
it doesn't get weird.

01:29:54.258 --> 01:29:56.391
To this day,
I don't know what happened.

01:29:56.478 --> 01:29:58.088
I don't. I don't.
All of a sudden,

01:29:58.175 --> 01:30:00.960
it went from them
loving me to them hating me.

01:30:01.047 --> 01:30:04.311
But maybe I'm not that funny,
so I'm not that fucked-up.

01:30:04.399 --> 01:30:05.922
That's the consolation.

01:30:06.009 --> 01:30:08.359
The best type
of conversation you'll have,

01:30:08.446 --> 01:30:10.361
you're talking,

01:30:10.448 --> 01:30:12.581
and someone's
listening, right?

01:30:12.668 --> 01:30:15.018
It's the narcissist
fantasy.

01:30:15.105 --> 01:30:18.456
Don't be--
don't ruin it for everybody.

01:30:18.543 --> 01:30:19.892
[Pollak]
With your feelings.

01:30:19.979 --> 01:30:21.459
Exactly.

01:30:21.546 --> 01:30:24.506
This whole thing about
feelings, I just--

01:30:24.593 --> 01:30:25.724
I couldn't absorb it.

01:30:25.811 --> 01:30:26.856
[Pollak]
Yeah.

01:30:26.943 --> 01:30:28.684
Even though I had them.

01:30:28.771 --> 01:30:31.338
I made a girl cry
in college.

01:30:35.778 --> 01:30:37.519
[muffled laugh]

01:30:37.606 --> 01:30:39.216
I feel bad.

01:30:39.303 --> 01:30:41.697
I'm a horrible person.
They hate me.

01:30:41.784 --> 01:30:43.525
This is the end
of my life and career.

01:30:43.612 --> 01:30:44.874
I will never recover.

01:30:44.961 --> 01:30:46.353
They will never
like me again.

01:30:46.441 --> 01:30:47.920
I'm stupid, I'm--

01:30:48.007 --> 01:30:50.923
It's all of that
put together.

01:30:51.010 --> 01:30:52.534
I used to be
a smart-ass in class,

01:30:52.621 --> 01:30:54.405
